'''Sieradz Land''' ({{lang-pl|Ziemia Sieradzka}}) is a historical region of Poland, the southeastern part of [[Greater Poland]]. It has been also the name of the administrative unit from 14th-18th centuries (former [[Duchy of Sieradz]]) of the same borders (and a little different from the [[Sieradz Voivodeship]], which included furthermore smaller [[Wieluń Land]]); the [[sejmik]] used to be held in [[Szadek]]. It has been a part of [[Archdiocese of Gniezno]], and [[Uniejów]] used to be a residence of the [[primate (bishop)|primate]]. It has 9,700&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> and about 950,000 inhabitants. Its traditional capital is [[Sieradz]], while other bigger cities are [[Piotrków Trybunalski]] (another historically important locality), [[Radomsko]], [[Tomaszów Mazowiecki]] (partly in [[Łęczyca Land]]), [[Bełchatów]], [[Zduńska Wola]], and [[Pabianice]] (a suburb of [[Łódź]]). It lies at the [[Warta]] and on the left bank of [[Pilica (river)|Pilica]] rivers, and these are mainly forested areas.
